Whith this pull request you can call yunohost app listmodules to get modules listed in /usr/share/yunohost/admin/modules/.
The web api is called like that https://yunohost.local/yunohost/api/modules . There is no need to authenticate (because the adminjs password is not available when adminjs is loading). The result is like this:
{"modules": ["helloworld", "menu", "usersubscribe"]}

is subprocess.call(['sudo', 'reboot']) right ?

Yes, but you may want to use subprocess.check_call(['sudo', 'reboot']) that will raise a subprocess.CalledProcessError in case the underlying command do not return a zero-status.
@opi why are you suggesting sudo whereas @polytan02 does not ?

@stevenroose Yes, the way I try to do it should work with multiple domain.
The default for a new domain is to use let's encrypt unless if --noletsencrypt option is used.
I also included theses lines https://github.com/mbugeia/yunohost/blob/letsencrypt/data/hooks/conf_regen/16-letsencrypt#L26-L31 to perform automatic cert generation for existing domains, but I'm not sure it should be automatic so I will probably remove them.

Hey there,
I just discovered the issue tracker and dev chat of yunohost, as well as this topic. Didn't realize some people were already working on let's encrypt integration before my tuto/package :P
Is there any progress on this ? Though I'm new, I'd be willing to try to contribute to a proper integration. Here's my opinion on @mbugeia questions :

I agree that the LE official client is pretty heavy. Didn't try acme_tiny or simp_le yet, but they sound great ;
Not sure about the revoke, but I think it does no harm to have it ;
LE shouldn't be the default

So this is mostly done. Still need to test a few things though (such as the cron job working as expected, and the postinstall correctly adding the default list + cron job)(also need to test the migration in real life situation).
Major changes :

Basically reworked app_listlists, app_fetchlist, app_removelist from ~scratch ;
Applists url are now stored in a .url in same directory as .json ;
app_fetchlist fetches all registered lists ;
Got rid of the cron jobs who re-wrote themselves, now there's a single yunohost-fetch-applists cronjob in /etc/cron.daily simply calling yunohost app fetchlist ;
Migration should be transparent : calling  app_listlists or app_fetchlist will trigger, if needed, a migration to register properly the lists (with a .url), remove the legacy cron jobs, and install the new cronjob ;
I added unit tests for basically all of this. Basically first time writing unit tests, hope I got them right ;
